Title:
KslKatz — BYOVD Credential Extractor using Microsoft Defender’s KslD.sys

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
KslKatz is a standalone Windows credential extraction tool that uses a Microsoft-signed Defender driver (KslD.sys) as a BYOVD primitive to read kernel/physical memory and bypass LSASS PPL protections. It abuses an older vulnerable KslD.sys left on disk to expose an unrestricted `MmCopyMemory`-backed IOCTL read (plus info leaks for KASLR defeat), enabling direct physical reads of LSASS memory. The tool locates LSASS and required secrets by leaking kernel pointers via `NtQuerySystemInformation(SystemHandleInformation)`, walking EPROCESS lists, and performing manual page-table translation from LSASS DTB/CR3. It avoids noisy remote memory scanning by signature-scanning `lsasrv.dll` and `wdigest.dll` from disk (no `LoadLibrary`), then reads only the needed structures from LSASS to extract MSV1_0 NT/LM/SHA1 hashes and WDigest cleartext (when caching is enabled). It is primarily useful for red teams and pentesters with local admin who want a “living-off-the-land” style LSASS credential theft path using only Microsoft-signed components. It’s notable because it highlights a practical gap in driver blocklisting (Microsoft drivers excluded) and a “no CVE / no fix” posture despite a powerful kernel read primitive.

Technical Focus:
- BYOVD via Microsoft Defender KslD.sys (service ImagePath swap to vulnerable binary)
- Arbitrary kernel/physical memory read via IOCTL (SubCmd 12) and KASLR leak (SubCmd 2)
- PPL bypass by reading LSASS through physical memory + manual page table walks (CR3/DTB)
- EPROCESS discovery via handle table kernel pointer leak (SystemHandleInformation)
- Local on-disk signature scanning of lsasrv.dll/wdigest.dll to resolve internal globals
- LSA secrets decryption (AES-CFB128 / 3DES-CBC) and BCRYPT key structure traversal

Use Cases:
- Dump MSV1_0 credential material (NT/LM/SHA1) from PPL-protected LSASS with local admin
- Extract WDigest cleartext passwords when caching is enabled or has been enabled in-memory
- Post-exploitation credential access without third-party vulnerable drivers (Microsoft-signed only)
- Research/validation of Defender driver exposure, blocklist limitations, and kernel read primitives
- Building detections around suspicious KslD service reconfiguration and `\\.\KslD` access

Keywords:
KslKatz, KslD.sys, Microsoft Defender, BYOVD, MmCopyMemory, IOCTL 0x222044, Protected Process Light, LSASS, credential dumping, MSV1_0, WDigest, LogonSessionList, l_LogSessList, NtQuerySystemInformation, SystemHandleInformation, EPROCESS, ActiveProcessLinks, CR3, DTB, page table walk, KASLR bypass, ChangeServiceConfigW, AllowedProcessName, Windows CNG, bcrypt.dll, AES-CFB128, 3DES-CBC, DriverSiPolicy.p7b, HVCI, vulnerable driver blocklist